posts.author: gusick
posts.text:
No, I wouldn't worry about one jam. Ducks don't shoot back so that's just a minor inconvenience. All guns do that from time to time. There are no exceptions, I've had revolvers, Glocks, and AK47s malfunction on me. Some guns are better than others, but there is no such thing as a foolproof gun.
And yes, cleaning it helps.

stormguild.us
Storm is a Cutting Edge 2-Day Mythic Progression Guild founded in June-2016. While maintaining a laid back and friendly environment, we pride ourselves on killing the hardest content available. Our reduced schedule compared to other similarly progressed guilds allow us to spend time doing other things in game and out. Previous Mythic raiding experience The desire to min/max your character(s) and stay on the forefront of theorycrafting The ability to play all roles for your class effectively Consistent TOP-TIER level of play. Check guild website daily Ability to come to raid prepared, this includes, but not limited to, bringing enough consumables an[ul]d having knowledge of fights we are working on. Near perfect attendance required to remain on our raid roster. Loot is handled via loot council. We feel this is the best way to improve the guild as a whole. We are mature adults and as such, respect is mandatory to all players internally and externally of Storm. Members are preferred to be the age of 21 or older, but exceptions can be made under the right circumstances. posts.author: ☼Another☼
posts.text:
The IC is posted. For right now, I'm keeping each kingdom in their own spoiler. If kingdoms choose to make their actions public, or any other information, that is there prerogative. Until that point, please do not view other players' spoilers.
The map, such as it is, should give relative ideas of where people are. If you have an issue with where you are placed for whatever reason, let me know. My artistic skill should be beyond, or more likely below, reproach.
If you choose to engage in covert diplomacy, please CC me on the pms. This is so that I can clarify questions as they arise, and also so that, if I choose to write up previous turns as a short synopsis, I can directly Quote: exchanges.
Please submit your turn within 2 days of a turn being posted, and I will attempt to have a post within 1 day of the last response. If I can't accomplish that, I'll let you know as far in advance as I can. If two days have passed without a post, your kingdom will simply be simulated for a turn. If your kingdom is run as an AI for more than three turns (one week of unexplained absence), it may either be given to a new player, or otherwise removed. If you do need to take an extended absence, let me know and I'll just simulate your empire for the intervening turns.
Quote: from: Blood_Librarian on December 06, 2017, 09:54:08 pm one question I do have to ask, Do you plan on one united magic system or similar?
Right now we have everything from eldritch horrors to immortal vampires. I'd rather leave the magic up to the players to flesh out for the moment, just so we don't end up constructing something that doesn't work for everyone. In general, if I don't have a set system when you want to do something, you can probably take some liberties with how it works. So, in short, not in particular, I don't plan to do a unified magic system.

posts.author: Gildaboh7581
posts.title: Breastfeeding advice
posts.text:
I formula fed my first and am 12wks into breastfeeding my second and I cannot recommend breastfeeding enough!!! They both woke/wake often to feed so please don't think you'll necessarily get more sleep ff 😂 Boobing is just s much easier! I'd also not realised the importance of doing as nature intended before now....which is very un 'me' 😂 My daughter was in her own room at a week old and my son is in bed with us, with her I battled to get into routines and spent her whole younger years (she's now 19!) struggling and not enjoying it but this time I'm going with the flow and literally loving it all!! Which is funny as he had a tongue tie and cranial issues which resulted in big open wounds on both nipples for about 6-7wks, I had a blocked duct, more bits of nipple missing (as his mouth grew my nip rubbed on a different bit as he has a very high pallet which left craters out the end of my nips), and now have thrush but it's still better in my opinion than formula feeding. My daughter had horrendous colic and would scream from about 8pm til midnight daily until about 4mnths, my son's had tummy ache three times and infacol has worked a treat each time. He's such a contended babe, as am I even though on paper I should probably be climbing the walls 😂
Sorry for rambling x x

thread.title: Starry Night: 2017
thread.title_full: Starry Night: 2017

posts.author: ridgeway307
posts.title: Starry Night: 2017
posts.text:
My Writing Challenge for today, kindly set up by Liz, is to write a Tea Towel Blog about a Christmas Tea Towel but not to use the words ‘Christmas’, ‘Tea’ or ‘Towel’. I write very quickly, you can probably tell that, without thinking about my use of words, whether I have been repetitious or not. So the purpose of the Challenge is to slow my writing down and help me become more thoughtful as to the use of language.
Starry Night, a Sophie Allport classic, is the newest addition to my Collection. I had promised myself there would be no more festive kitchen cloths unless it was something special, and this is. It is a delight, summoning up all the best bits about this time of year: snow, Santa Claus, sacks of presents, sleigh ride, reindeer, snowmen and loads of stars; this is a child’s dream. Personally, I love Sophie Allport’s style: usually a grey background with white illustrations and a hint of colour. At this time of the year, red is an appropriate colour, on Santa’s suit and sleigh, on the snowman’s hat and the iconic post box; the red draws you to the important images of this scene. The subtle use of greens and fawns is very clever, never distracting from the overall image.
For me, this wiping up cloth, really makes me think of the festive season and everything I love about it: friends and family in contact, cards, the Newsletters that everyone, except me, complains about, carols, Midnight Service, crackers, trees, lots of wrapping paper, fairy lights (not flashing ones), wreaths on the front door, presents under tree, mince pies, the inevitable pudding with a few coins tossed in as a health and safety hazard, decorations, loads of decorations and of course the ‘special’ wiping up cloths. This is the season where family traditions come into play. I love it.
But this cloth also reminds me of my favourite seasonal activity: the Festive Films. From about mid November there are at least three films on in the afternoon, every day. I record them all. I can divide them into three categories: the absolute rubbish and you know this after about two minutes and they can be deleted; the exceptionally good, usually with well known actors that would standalone as great films all year round, like ‘Love Actually’, ‘The Holiday’ or ‘Miracle on 34th Street’ (both versions) and the ‘Mrs Miracle’ series. The third category is a classic seasonal film with a standard format: usually the opening scene is covered in snow (either in New York or the countryside), often at least one parent has died about two or three years ago, always a child wanting a family or a business is going bust, estranged families and it always has a happy ending; if there is a strong woman character she either works in advertising or runs a bakery; sometimes there are angels, maybe the film starts in childhood and then moving on twenty years. They are the sort of film you can curl up on the sofa and watch when it is cold and windy outside or if you have a cold and are feeling sorry for yourself or if you have had a hard day at work. Virtually all the seasonal films are American and there are actors whose careers seem to be devoted to these films. These are the good quality seasonal films but will never win an Oscar; if Dean Cain is in it, it will be good giving you that ‘feel good’ factor. These are films that you can watch time and again and usually starts by me saying “I remember this one. Her mother died and she’s in advertising…”.
The little scene at the bottom of the wiping up cloth is reminiscent of the opening scene of many festive films and I love it (and them). It reminds me of good and happy times (these are not films to be watched when you are sad) and what this season is all about. Thanks to Sophie Allport for not ‘rubbishing’ nostalgia.

posts.text: Movie Beastmaster III: The Eye of Braxus (1996) download free Book Title: Beastmaster III: The Eye of Braxus Directors: Gabrielle Beaumont Genre: Action, Adventure, Fantasy, Sci-Fi Release Date: 1996-05-24 Stars: Marc Singer,Tony Todd,Keith Coulouris IMDb Rating: 3.9 Language: English   "Beastmaster III: The Eye of Braxus": Before he died, Dar's father gave a mysterious amulet to Tal, Dar's younger brother who is now king. Dar, while wandering with his animal companions, chances to meet and rescue a family who seek the help of King Tal against Lord Agon, a sorcerer who has conquered their land. Dar obtains an audience for them with Tal, who rallies his troops to march against Agon in the morning. Alas, the young king is captured by Agon's crimson warriors during the night. It is the amulet -- the Eye of the imprisoned god Braxus -- that Agon really wants. But Dar now carries half of it, and is nowhere to be found. Will he fall into Lord Agon's clutches when he comes to free his brother? Reviews of the Beastmaster III: The Eye of Braxus What was Marc Singer thinking? Was he truly that desperate for work, or was this just a fulfillment of some contractual obligation? Either way, he should be deeply ashamed of appearing in this turkey. The original Beastmaster was a wonderful film with a great deal of originality but the sequels have progressively deteriorated into farce.I can't begin to tell you how bad this movie is. Memorable moments include Dar's Lion buddy, who clearly is too old to do his own stuntwork anymore (Old=not likely to attack the actors) so they employ a lioness to do the scenes where he gets caught in a net. Lion with a mane becomes lioness without one. Hmmm...that's not noticeable at all...no sir!Suffice to say it's only saving grace is the finale where Dar (Singer) fights some demon lord. Why is this bit the best? Is it action packed? Is it full of great special effects? No. It's the best because it's just so farcical you'll be in stitches with laughter throughout it. The creature is a cross between a teenage mutant turtle and the Papa Dinosaur from the "Dinosaurs" TV series. Comical doesn't even begin to describe how this "evil" demon looks. It has all the menace of a Jim Henson muppet.Ads if that weren't enough we are also treated to an early performance from Casper van Dien as some supposed king. Yep, that's believable....not. In fact, of all the cast, the only ones who even looked comfortable with their roles were Marc Singer and David Warner (yes, he's the bad guy - no surprise there). The rest were a mixture of woefully bad acting and miscasting.One other thing of interest. Marc Singer now actually looks like he has spent a lifetime wandering the wilderness with nothing more than a loincloth to protect him from the elements. So that much was realistic.SUMMARY: Watch it, grit your teeth, then laugh at the dumb finale. He installs his robots as tellers, and despite his criminal past, seems to be running things in perfect order. The Dynamic Duo realize they will have to trick him into making a mistake in order to remove him. They go to work on a plan to gain control of his robots. But that plan is jeopardized when, due to an odd turn of events, Batman's true identity Bruce Wayne is declared mentally ill and hauled off in a straight-jacket. Reviews of the Batman The Joker's Epitaph "The Joker's Epitaph" begins in ominous fashion, Bruce Wayne being forced to pull the lever that will squash Robin into the shape of a flat comic book. Fortunately, Alfred is just outside disguised as Batman, overcoming his vertigo long enough to make a Batclimb to the spot where Robin's ready to bite the dust. A pellet of Batgas is enough for The Joker (Cesar Romero) and his cohorts to make their escape, fortuitously with the document signed by Bruce Wayne appointing him vice chairman of the board of the Gotham National Bank. Legally bound by the document, there's nothing that can undo what has been done, but it's enough for Commissioner Gordon to send Chief O'Hara out to arrest an obviously insane Bruce Wayne and take him away in a strait-jacket! The Joker is already thinking ahead in devising a plan to blackmail Bruce Wayne, using a recording of his confession of embezzlement to force him to wed the beautiful Josie Miller (Phyllis Douglas), who confesses that she'll always be faithful: "in my fashion!" Finding the right circuit to reprogram robot teller Mr. Glee (Lawrence Montaigne), Batman sets the wheels in motion for the bank just as the Chief arrives with trusty strait-jacket, though Alfred and Robin follow closely in the Batmobile to help Bruce Wayne back into cape and cowl, racing to the Gotham National Bank to see what happens. The Joker is none too pleased to have Commissioner Gordon dismiss him as vice chairman of the board, but Josie insists they still have Bruce Wayne on the hook. Just then, Mr. Glee shows up to embrace wife Josie, after which Joker's robot tellers begin holding up customers. Only when he orders all three robots to disregard previous instructions does he entrap himself, the inevitable Batfight taking place right there in the bank. The final scene features Oscar Beregi as Teutonic quack Dr. Floyd, who amends his earlier diagnosis of Bruce Wayne's complete insanity, announcing his full recovery, but when he laments that he couldn't examine Batman as well, Wayne suggests that his own brain patterns would not be dissimilar. This is more than an exasperated Chief O'Hara can take: "mother o' mercy, get the smellin' salts, Mr. Wayne is havin' a relapse!" This possible ad lib is enough for even the stone faced Neil Hamilton to burst out laughing! Even at this late stage in the series good writing was still in evidence, enabling Cesar Romero to score another triumph for W.C. Whiteface. Phyllis Douglas is best remembered for two episodes of STAR TREK, "The Galileo Seven" and "The Way to Eden," while Lawrence Montaigne would play an equally stone faced Vulcan in second season opener "Amok Time" (he'd already portrayed a Romulan in "Balance of Terror"). Planning To Pursue An MBA (DS & DA) At SCIT? We Have All The Essential Information You Seek! SCIT - Thursday, December 7, 2017. Submitted by scit . 
Thinking of pursuing an MBA in Data Sciences and Data Analytics from SCIT Pune? You’ve arrived at the right place! Let us take a quick look at the Master of Business Administration (DS & DA) course at the Symbiosis Centre for Information Technology, one of the most renowned institutes offering an MBA in Information Technology ! 
A little about the institute… 
SCIT is a top-rated Information Technology Business School that is renowned for honing and nurturing quality IT talent. The institute helps transform capable managerial students into IT industry leaders using an advanced training pedagogy and a futuristic computer lab. At SCIT, a heavy emphasis is placed upon converting talented prospective leaders into technological thought-leaders of the future. 
Is SCIT the right place for pursuing my future education? 
The answer to this question is a definite “Yes”! As a matter of fact, the exceptionally well-crafted, out-of-the-box training methodologies at SCIT transform students into highly skilled techno-managers capable of dealing with the many pressures of working in the IT domain. Not just that, their path-breaking Information Technology Business Management programme (that is counted amongst the very best IT MBA programmes out there) provides students with immense benefits in terms of learning and skill development. This gives SCIT students a major advantage over all other students when it comes to finding employment (in the IT industry). 
Is the Data Analytics programme at SCIT recommended? 
Most certainly. As it goes, the programme has been tailored mainly towards training students in the complete and comprehensive art of mastering data analysis techniques. As a result, getting an MBA in Data Analytics and Data Sciences helps students recognize the many ways by which data use can be optimized within a blossoming business organization to take commercially sound decisions. 
This programme essentially takes a thorough look at the many varied facets of data analytics – specifically programming for data sciences and data mining to name a few. Such comprehensive learning pedagogy helps prospective IT-management professionals graduating from SCIT add value to an organization’s resource-usage methodologies by effectively making all data-specific processes economical and viable. 
With this, we bring this quick analysis of the various programmes offered at SCIT to a conclusion. It is hoped that this gives you a general idea of what to expect from a Master of Business Administration degree in Data Sciences and Data Analytics at SCIT. Apart from this programme, SCIT is also seen as the best institute for pursuing an Executive MBA in Pune . You can find the full details of this programme at their official website. We wish you all a fantastic management career ahead! Thank you for reading! About SCIT “We at SCIT have the vision to be a world class IT B-School known for creating global IT Professionals and are doing every bit to achieve it in real time. We also promote a holistic learning wherein the students learn from various modes like presentations, Group Discussions, Role-plays and debates which enhances their communication and interpersonal skills.” Says Director , a SCIT spokesperson. For more information, please visit: - http://www.scit.edu/

posts.title: Vsyo reshayet mgnoveniye
posts.text: Stars: Galina Belyaeva,Olga Ageyeva,Boris Zajdenberg IMDb Rating: 7.1 Language: Russian   "Vsyo reshayet mgnoveniye": A story of a Russian girl Nadya Privalova, a record-braking swimmer. She grew up by the sea, and learned swimming with a dolphin named "Fregat". Her first coach encouraged Nadya, and she took swimming professionally. She could beat the world record during her practice routine. But in public she suffered a classic "stage fright" syndrome, and she could not win any international competition. Now her participation in the Olympic games is at stake... . Can she overcome..? Reviews of the Vsyo reshayet mgnoveniye This film is about a young girl Nadya, who lived near the sea and liked to compete in swimming with her friend, a dolphin Fregat. Her another friend, non-professional provincial trainer, even did not trained her, just constantly suggested Nadya to show her skills in official competitions. He was nine years elder and had no other thoughts or wishes concerning her. But Nadya loved him and this was the main reason of choosing the "big sport", leaving Fregat alone for some time. However, while she easily, without any additional training, won (setting new records BTW) all events prior to international competitions, she could not swim well in latter ones. She knew, that million eyes are looking at her and feared.Even I, who watched many masterpieces prior to this, was shocked, watching this film. The Great play by Galina Belyaeva, this was her first role, but she LIVED in the film. Very good play by other actors and magic music throughout the film resulted in absolutely fantastic atmosphere of the whole movie. I strongly suggest those, who think, that Olympic Games were always only doping scandals and Olympic Champions were always like cyborgs, to watch this film. You'll understand, what were Olympic Champions like in the best years of Olympic Movement.I really don't know, where you can get it. I didn't found any DVDs or VHSs available online. I watched it on the Russian channel "Nashe kino", thats all, what I can say on this question. If you'll be lucky to find it somewhere, I am sure, you'll be shocked not less than I was after watching it.
